text:
Build and run the query
For each sex and 5-year age bracket, how many MBS services were used in 2015 and how much was charged?


Code
tic("Three-table join on 372M MBS rows")
result &lt;- demo |&gt;
  select(spine_id, core_gender, year_of_birth) |&gt;
  inner_join(dhda_spine, by = "spine_id") |&gt;
  inner_join(
    mbs |&gt; select(synthetic_aeuid, numserv, feecharged),
    by = "synthetic_aeuid"
  ) |&gt;
  mutate(
    age_2015  = 2015L - year_of_birth,
    age_group = as.integer(floor(age_2015 / 5) * 5)
  ) |&gt;
  filter(age_2015 &gt;= 0L, age_2015 &lt; 100L) |&gt;
  group_by(core_gender, age_group) |&gt;
  summarise(
    services    = sum(numserv, na.rm = TRUE),
    fee_charged = sum(feecharged, na.rm = TRUE),
    claims      = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) |&gt;
  collect()
toc()


Three-table join on 372M MBS rows: 6.451 sec elapsed


Code
result







That joined 30 million demographic records through 30 million spine records to 372 million MBS claims, bucketed by age, and collected a tidy result — in the time shown above.
Here’s the SQL dbplyr generated:


Code
demo |&gt;
  select(spine_id, core_gender, year_of_birth) |&gt;
  inner_join(dhda_spine, by = "spine_id") |&gt;
  inner_join(mbs |&gt; select(synthetic_aeuid, numserv, feecharged), by = "synthetic_aeuid") |&gt;
  mutate(age_2015 = 2015L - year_of_birth,
         age_group = as.integer(floor(age_2015 / 5) * 5)) |&gt;
  filter(age_2015 &gt;= 0L, age_2015 &lt; 100L) |&gt;
  group_by(core_gender, age_group) |&gt;
  summarise(services = sum(numserv, na.rm = TRUE),
            fee_charged = sum(feecharged, na.rm = TRUE),
            claims = n(), .groups = "drop") |&gt;
  show_query()


&lt;SQL&gt;
SELECT
  core_gender,
  age_group,
  SUM(numserv) AS services,
  SUM(feecharged) AS fee_charged,
  COUNT(*) AS claims
FROM (
  SELECT q01.*, CAST(FLOOR(age_2015 / 5.0) * 5.0 AS INTEGER) AS age_group
  FROM (
    SELECT q01.*, 2015 - year_of_birth AS age_2015
    FROM (
      SELECT
        demo.SPINE_ID AS spine_id,
        CORE_GENDER AS core_gender,
        YEAR_OF_BIRTH AS year_of_birth,
        dhda_spine.SYNTHETIC_AEUID AS synthetic_aeuid,
        NUMSERV AS numserv,
        FEECHARGED AS feecharged
      FROM demo
      INNER JOIN dhda_spine
        ON (demo.SPINE_ID = dhda_spine.spine_id)
      INNER JOIN mbs
        ON (dhda_spine.SYNTHETIC_AEUID = mbs.SYNTHETIC_AEUID)
    ) q01
  ) q01
  WHERE (age_2015 &gt;= 0) AND (age_2015 &lt; 100)
) q01
GROUP BY core_gender, age_group

Step 1: Derive employer switches from STP (chunked)
An employer switch is when abn_hash_trunc changes from one week to the next. We use lag() with a window_order() clause — but process 10 hash buckets independently so each fits in memory.


Code
n_buckets &lt;- 10

bucket_switches &lt;- function(b) {
  stp |&gt;
    filter(bucket == b) |&gt;
    select(synthetic_aeuid, week_ending, abn_hash_trunc,
           gross_pay = pmt_sumry_totl_grs_pmt_amt) |&gt;
    group_by(synthetic_aeuid) |&gt;
    window_order(week_ending) |&gt;
    mutate(prev_employer = lag(abn_hash_trunc)) |&gt;
    ungroup() |&gt;
    filter(!is.na(prev_employer),
           abn_hash_trunc != prev_employer) |&gt;
    transmute(synthetic_aeuid,
              week_ending,
              new_employer = abn_hash_trunc,
              prev_employer,
              gross_pay)
}

tic("Derive employer switches (10 buckets, from parquet)")
stp_switches &lt;- map(0:(n_buckets - 1), \(b) bucket_switches(b) |&gt; compute()) |&gt;
  reduce(union_all) |&gt;
  compute(name = "stp_switches", temporary = FALSE, overwrite = TRUE)
toc()


Derive employer switches (10 buckets, from parquet): 44.747 sec elapsed


Code
n_switches  &lt;- stp_switches |&gt; summarise(n = n()) |&gt; pull(n)
n_switchers &lt;- stp_switches |&gt; summarise(n = n_distinct(synthetic_aeuid)) |&gt; pull(n)
cat("Switches:", comma(n_switches), "across", comma(n_switchers), "people\n")


Switches: 0 across 0 people


Every step is tidyverse. bucket_switches(b) is a lazy pipeline that reads ~70M STP rows for one bucket, drops down to four columns (keeping memory small during the sort), applies lag() partitioned by person, and keeps only the rows where the employer actually changed. map() runs the pipeline once per bucket; compute() writes each bucket’s result to a small temp table inside DuckDB. reduce(union_all) stacks the ten temp tables into one lazy query, and the final compute(name = "stp_switches", temporary = FALSE) writes the combined result out as a persistent table.






NoteWhy chunking works



lag() here is partitioned by synthetic_aeuid. Every person’s timeline belongs to exactly one bucket, so processing one bucket at a time gives the same answer as doing all 30 million people at once. Each iteration only has to sort 70M rows, which fits in 20 GB.
Running lag() on the full 700M-row table blows past the memory budget and the process is killed — see A4 for the full failure log.








TipSelf-join as an alternative to lag()



For fixed-interval lags (exactly 7 days here), you can replace lag() with a self-join. Shift the “previous” week forward by 7 days, then inner-join on equality:
stp_b    &lt;- stp |&gt; filter(bucket == 0L)
stp_prev &lt;- stp_b |&gt;
  transmute(synthetic_aeuid,
            week_ending   = week_ending + 7L,
            prev_employer = abn_hash_trunc)

stp_b |&gt;
  inner_join(stp_prev, by = c("synthetic_aeuid", "week_ending")) |&gt;
  filter(abn_hash_trunc != prev_employer)
This works because STP records are always exactly 7 days apart. It does not work if the gap between records is irregular — for that, stick with lag(), which just looks back one row regardless of the time gap. At 70M rows per bucket the two approaches run in similar time (2-4s each). See A4 for the full comparison.

Step 3: Link switches to shocks via spine
STP uses ATO identifiers; MBS uses DHDA identifiers. The spine tables bridge them via shared spine_id. The linkage is a double join: ATO-aeuid → spine_id → DHDA-aeuid.


Code
tic("Cross-spine join: switches x shocks")
crosswalk &lt;- ato_spine  |&gt; select(ato_aeuid  = synthetic_aeuid, spine_id) |&gt;
  inner_join(dhda_spine |&gt; select(dhda_aeuid = synthetic_aeuid, spine_id),
             by = "spine_id") |&gt;
  select(ato_aeuid, dhda_aeuid)

shocks_via_dhda &lt;- mbs_shocks |&gt;
  select(dhda_aeuid = synthetic_aeuid, shock_month)

post_shock &lt;- stp_switches |&gt;
  inner_join(crosswalk,       by = c("synthetic_aeuid" = "ato_aeuid")) |&gt;
  inner_join(shocks_via_dhda, by = "dhda_aeuid") |&gt;
  filter(week_ending &gt;= shock_month,
         week_ending &lt;  shock_month + days(90L)) |&gt;
  mutate(switch_month = floor_date(week_ending, "month")) |&gt;
  group_by(switch_month) |&gt;
  summarise(switches_post_shock = n(),
            people              = n_distinct(synthetic_aeuid),
            .groups = "drop") |&gt;
  arrange(switch_month) |&gt;
  collect()
toc()


Cross-spine join: switches x shocks: 0.557 sec elapsed


Code
post_shock







Three joins, one date filter, one groupby. No SQL.
shock_month + days(90L) just works: dbplyr translates it to DuckDB’s date arithmetic, so “within three months of the shock” is a plain filter().

Step 4: Query with dbplyr
Now you are in the pleasant part. Open a read-only connection (so multiple R sessions can share it) and use dplyr verbs as usual. This is the same recipe case study 1 and case study 2 use.


Code
con &lt;- dbConnect(
  duckdb::duckdb(),
  dbdir = file.path(paths$duckdb_dir, "plida_tables.duckdb"),
  read_only = TRUE
)

demo       &lt;- tbl(con, "demo")
dhda_spine &lt;- tbl(con, "dhda_spine")
mbs        &lt;- tbl(con, "mbs")

tic("Three-table join + groupby on 372M rows")
result &lt;- demo |&gt;
  select(SPINE_ID, CORE_GENDER, YEAR_OF_BIRTH) |&gt;
  inner_join(dhda_spine |&gt; rename(SPINE_ID = spine_id), by = "SPINE_ID") |&gt;
  inner_join(mbs |&gt; select(SYNTHETIC_AEUID, NUMSERV, BTOS), by = "SYNTHETIC_AEUID") |&gt;
  mutate(age_2015 = 2015L - YEAR_OF_BIRTH,
         age_group = (age_2015 %/% 10L) * 10L) |&gt;
  filter(age_2015 &gt;= 0L, age_2015 &lt; 100L) |&gt;
  group_by(CORE_GENDER, age_group, BTOS) |&gt;
  summarise(services = sum(NUMSERV, na.rm = TRUE),
            claims = n(), .groups = "drop") |&gt;
  collect()
toc()


Three-table join + groupby on 372M rows: 2.568 sec elapsed


Code
result







That joined 30 million people to 372 million MBS claims, grouped by sex, decade of age, and broad type of service, and returned a tidy tibble. All in a few seconds.

dbplyr is the day-to-day interface
Once the DuckDB file exists, every actual query should go through dbplyr. You get the dplyr verbs you already know, they are translated to SQL, and DuckDB executes them using its vectorised engine. For example:
library(duckdb); library(DBI); library(dplyr); library(dbplyr)

con &lt;- dbConnect(duckdb::duckdb(),
                 dbdir = "plida_tables.duckdb",
                 read_only = TRUE)

demo       &lt;- tbl(con, "demo")
dhda_spine &lt;- tbl(con, "dhda_spine")
mbs        &lt;- tbl(con, "mbs")

demo |&gt;
  select(SPINE_ID, CORE_GENDER, YEAR_OF_BIRTH) |&gt;
  inner_join(dhda_spine |&gt; rename(SPINE_ID = spine_id), by = "SPINE_ID") |&gt;
  inner_join(mbs |&gt; select(SYNTHETIC_AEUID, NUMSERV), by = "SYNTHETIC_AEUID") |&gt;
  mutate(age_bucket = sql("(2015 - YEAR_OF_BIRTH) / 10 * 10")) |&gt;
  group_by(CORE_GENDER, age_bucket) |&gt;
  summarise(services = sum(NUMSERV, na.rm = TRUE),
            rows = n(), .groups = "drop") |&gt;
  collect()
A few points of good practice here:

read_only = TRUE lets multiple R sessions attach the same DuckDB file simultaneously — useful when you are iterating in one session and knitting a Quarto doc in another.
tbl(con, "name") returns a lazy dbplyr table. Nothing runs until collect().
sql(...) inside mutate is the escape hatch when a SQL idiom has no dplyr translation (here, integer division plus bucketing). You stay inside the dplyr pipe, but drop to raw SQL where needed. Use this freely — it is not cheating.
collect() at the end is what actually runs the query; everything upstream is just building the SQL. Never call collect() mid-pipeline unless you know you need the intermediate result in R memory.

A first query: filter and count
A single year of ITR is ~10 million rows. Count how many returns are filed in 2015, by ANZSCO occupation major group.

DuckDBArrow




Code
itr_db |&gt;
  filter(incm_yr == 2015L, !is.na(ocptn_grp_cd)) |&gt;
  mutate(occ_major = as.integer(floor(ocptn_grp_cd / 1000))) |&gt;
  count(occ_major) |&gt;
  collect() |&gt;
  arrange(occ_major)












⏱️ filter + count (10M) (duckdb): 0.061s








Code
itr_ar |&gt;
  filter(incm_yr == 2015L, !is.na(ocptn_grp_cd)) |&gt;
  mutate(occ_major = as.integer(floor(ocptn_grp_cd / 1000))) |&gt;
  count(occ_major) |&gt;
  collect() |&gt;
  arrange(occ_major)












⏱️ filter + count (10M) (arrow): 0.113s







The code is identical except for the handle. The numbers match. Both finish in a fraction of a second — the parquet reader pushes the incm_yr == 2015 predicate down to the row-group level in arrow, and DuckDB does the equivalent on its native storage, so only the rows for 2015 ever hit the engine.






NoteWhy as.integer(floor(x / 1000)) and not x %/% 1000 or as.integer(x / 1000)?



Arrow’s translator does not consistently handle R’s integer-division operator %/%, so that is out. The obvious alternative — as.integer(x / 1000) — looks fine but produces different numbers across backends because of how each engine casts floating-point values to integers (see the as.integer() trap callout in the next section). Wrapping the division in floor() sidesteps the problem: both arrow and DuckDB translate floor() to a proper floor function that rounds toward −∞, so the numbers match exactly.

Groupby across all years
Same operation, now over ~170 million rows spanning ten financial years. The dplyr shape is unchanged — it does not care whether the query runs against one file or fifty.

DuckDBArrow




Code
occ_by_year_db &lt;- itr_db |&gt;
  filter(!is.na(ocptn_grp_cd)) |&gt;
  mutate(occ_major = as.integer(floor(ocptn_grp_cd / 1000))) |&gt;
  count(incm_yr, occ_major) |&gt;
  collect()
head(occ_by_year_db)












⏱️ groupby (170M) (duckdb): 0.259s








Code
occ_by_year_ar &lt;- itr_ar |&gt;
  filter(!is.na(ocptn_grp_cd)) |&gt;
  mutate(occ_major = as.integer(floor(ocptn_grp_cd / 1000))) |&gt;
  count(incm_yr, occ_major) |&gt;
  collect()
head(occ_by_year_ar)












⏱️ groupby (170M) (arrow): 0.326s









Code
occ_labels &lt;- c(
  "1" = "Managers", "2" = "Professionals", "3" = "Technicians",
  "4" = "Community/personal", "5" = "Clerical/admin",
  "6" = "Sales", "7" = "Machinery operators", "8" = "Labourers"
)

occ_by_year_db |&gt;
  filter(occ_major %in% 1:8) |&gt;
  mutate(occ_label = factor(occ_labels[as.character(occ_major)], levels = occ_labels)) |&gt;
  ggplot(aes(incm_yr, n, colour = occ_label)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 0.7) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = label_comma()) +
  labs(x = "Income year", y = "Tax returns filed", colour = "ANZSCO major group",
       title = "Returns by occupation group over a decade",
       subtitle = "170M rows scanned in under a second") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 11)









For a full scan, a groupby, and a collect(), arrow and DuckDB are indistinguishable. Both stream parquet (or stream native columns, in DuckDB’s case), both keep memory essentially flat, and both are two orders of magnitude faster than the equivalent read_parquet() |&gt; group_by() |&gt; summarise() against in-memory tibbles (see the benchmarks for the full comparison).

Joins
This is where arrow and DuckDB split.
For joins between small tables — a few million rows per side — arrow and DuckDB are both fast and the code is identical. As soon as one side of the join involves tens of millions of rows, arrow’s Acero engine starts to struggle: the hash tables are built less efficiently than DuckDB’s, and the process either slows to a crawl or is killed by the OS. Above 100 million rows on either side, arrow routinely loses and DuckDB wins.
We will walk through the four filtering-or-matching join types (inner, left, semi, anti) on a small working example where both tools behave well, and then demonstrate the big PLIDA-shaped joins where only DuckDB is practical. The dplyr code is identical across backends — only the handle changes.
The small working example is a classic labour-market question: who was a manager (ANZSCO major 1) in 2014 and is still a manager, or a non-manager, in 2015? Two ITR slices, each ~1.5 million rows, joined on synthetic_aeuid. Nothing else touches a 30-million-row table.


Code
mgrs_14_ar &lt;- itr_ar |&gt;
  filter(incm_yr == 2014L,
         ocptn_grp_cd &gt;= 1000L, ocptn_grp_cd &lt; 2000L) |&gt;
  select(synthetic_aeuid, occ_14 = ocptn_grp_cd)

y15_ar &lt;- itr_ar |&gt;
  filter(incm_yr == 2015L, !is.na(ocptn_grp_cd)) |&gt;
  select(synthetic_aeuid, occ_15 = ocptn_grp_cd)

mgrs_14_db &lt;- itr_db |&gt;
  filter(incm_yr == 2014L,
         ocptn_grp_cd &gt;= 1000L, ocptn_grp_cd &lt; 2000L) |&gt;
  select(synthetic_aeuid, occ_14 = ocptn_grp_cd)

y15_db &lt;- itr_db |&gt;
  filter(incm_yr == 2015L, !is.na(ocptn_grp_cd)) |&gt;
  select(synthetic_aeuid, occ_15 = ocptn_grp_cd)


Each of these lazy handles represents the filtered slice — the underlying data is untouched until a collect() is demanded.

Inner join: who filed in both years?
Intersection of the two year slices: people who appear as managers in 2014 and as anyone in 2015.

DuckDBArrow




Code
mgr_stayers_db &lt;- mgrs_14_db |&gt;
  inner_join(y15_db, by = "synthetic_aeuid") |&gt;
  mutate(
    occ_major_15 = as.integer(floor(occ_15 / 1000)),
    still_mgr    = occ_major_15 == 1L
  ) |&gt;
  count(occ_major_15, still_mgr) |&gt;
  collect()
head(mgr_stayers_db)












⏱️ inner join (1.5M × 10M) (duckdb): 0.139s








Code
mgr_stayers_ar &lt;- mgrs_14_ar |&gt;
  inner_join(y15_ar, by = "synthetic_aeuid") |&gt;
  mutate(
    occ_major_15 = as.integer(floor(occ_15 / 1000)),
    still_mgr    = occ_major_15 == 1L
  ) |&gt;
  count(occ_major_15, still_mgr) |&gt;
  collect()
head(mgr_stayers_ar)












⏱️ inner join (1.5M × 10M) (arrow): 0.456s









Code
occ_labels &lt;- c(
  "1" = "Managers", "2" = "Professionals", "3" = "Technicians",
  "4" = "Community/personal", "5" = "Clerical/admin",
  "6" = "Sales", "7" = "Machinery ops", "8" = "Labourers"
)
mgr_stayers_db |&gt;
  filter(occ_major_15 %in% 2:8) |&gt;
  mutate(occ_15_label = factor(occ_labels[as.character(occ_major_15)],
                               levels = occ_labels)) |&gt;
  ggplot(aes(occ_15_label, n)) +
  geom_col(fill = "#1b9e77") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = label_comma()) +
  labs(x = "ANZSCO major group in 2015", y = "Managers in 2014",
       title = "What managers did next (1-year)",
       subtitle = "People who reported ANZSCO 1 in 2014, across their 2015 occupation") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 11) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 20, hjust = 1))















WarningPush filters before joins, always



If you write inner_join(itr_ar, ...) |&gt; filter(incm_yr == 2015), arrow will try to build a hash table covering all 170M ITR rows before applying the filter — which OOMs on a 32 GB machine. Rewriting as inner_join(itr_ar |&gt; filter(incm_yr == 2015), ...) lets arrow push the predicate into the parquet reader and only ~10M rows ever enter the join. DuckDB’s optimiser does this transformation for you; arrow’s does not, reliably.




Left join: every manager, matched or not
A left join keeps every row from the left table. Non-matches get NA on the right-hand columns. Useful here for asking “of 2014 managers, who did NOT file in 2015?”

DuckDBArrow




Code
mgr_all_db &lt;- mgrs_14_db |&gt;
  left_join(y15_db, by = "synthetic_aeuid") |&gt;
  mutate(filed_2015 = !is.na(occ_15)) |&gt;
  count(filed_2015) |&gt;
  collect()
mgr_all_db












⏱️ left join (1.5M × 10M) (duckdb): 0.095s








Code
mgr_all_ar &lt;- mgrs_14_ar |&gt;
  left_join(y15_ar, by = "synthetic_aeuid") |&gt;
  mutate(filed_2015 = !is.na(occ_15)) |&gt;
  count(filed_2015) |&gt;
  collect()
mgr_all_ar












⏱️ left join (1.5M × 10M) (arrow): 0.364s









Semi and anti joins: who stayed, who left
semi_join() keeps rows from the left table that have at least one match on the right, without pulling the right-hand columns in. anti_join() keeps rows that have no match. Both are filtering joins — the output has the same columns as the left input.
For “2014 managers who did not file in 2015”:

DuckDBArrow




Code
mgr_exits_db &lt;- mgrs_14_db |&gt;
  anti_join(y15_db, by = "synthetic_aeuid") |&gt;
  summarise(n = n()) |&gt;
  collect()
mgr_exits_db












⏱️ anti join (1.5M vs 10M) (duckdb): 0.125s








Code
mgr_exits_ar &lt;- mgrs_14_ar |&gt;
  anti_join(y15_ar, by = "synthetic_aeuid") |&gt;
  summarise(n = n()) |&gt;
  collect()
mgr_exits_ar












⏱️ anti join (1.5M vs 10M) (arrow): 0.305s







And the complementary “2014 managers who did file in 2015” with semi_join() — same semantics as inner_join() |&gt; select(left cols only) |&gt; distinct(), but cheaper:

DuckDBArrow




Code
mgr_stayers_ct_db &lt;- mgrs_14_db |&gt;
  semi_join(y15_db, by = "synthetic_aeuid") |&gt;
  summarise(n = n()) |&gt;
  collect()
mgr_stayers_ct_db












⏱️ semi join (1.5M vs 10M) (duckdb): 0.106s








Code
mgr_stayers_ct_ar &lt;- mgrs_14_ar |&gt;
  semi_join(y15_ar, by = "synthetic_aeuid") |&gt;
  summarise(n = n()) |&gt;
  collect()
mgr_stayers_ct_ar












⏱️ semi join (1.5M vs 10M) (arrow): 0.304s













Tipsemi_join vs filter(x %in% ...)



A naive alternative is filter(aeuid %in% !!collect(y15)$aeuid). This is a landmine — it pulls the full right-hand identifier column into R memory. semi_join() / anti_join() keep the whole operation inside the engine. Always prefer the filtering-join form for large data.




Full join: union of two worlds
A full join keeps every row from both sides, filling NA where there is no match. A classic PLIDA question it answers: how many people appear in the ATO spine but not the DHDA spine, and vice versa? Arrow’s Acero engine is slow at full joins on 30M-row tables (it does not efficiently build hash indexes on the key column), so we show only DuckDB here. The dplyr code is identical to what arrow would accept; we simply do not run it.

DuckDBArrow (not run)




Code
spine_coverage_db &lt;- ato_sp_db |&gt;
  transmute(spine_id, in_ato = TRUE) |&gt;
  full_join(dhda_sp_db |&gt; transmute(spine_id, in_dhda = TRUE), by = "spine_id") |&gt;
  mutate(in_ato  = coalesce(in_ato,  FALSE),
         in_dhda = coalesce(in_dhda, FALSE)) |&gt;
  count(in_ato, in_dhda) |&gt;
  collect()
spine_coverage_db












⏱️ full join (30M × 30M) (duckdb): 0.545s








Code
# Arrow can express the same dplyr pipeline but, in practice, its Acero
# join engine on two 30M-row tables either takes many minutes or exhausts
# RAM on a 32 GB machine. We skip the timing and show the DuckDB version
# only.
ato_sp_ar  |&gt; transmute(spine_id, in_ato  = TRUE) |&gt;
  full_join(dhda_sp_ar |&gt; transmute(spine_id, in_dhda = TRUE), by = "spine_id") |&gt;
  mutate(in_ato  = coalesce(in_ato,  FALSE),
         in_dhda = coalesce(in_dhda, FALSE)) |&gt;
  count(in_ato, in_dhda) |&gt;
  collect()





In the synthetic fplida corpus every person is present in every spine, so the off-diagonals are zero. On real PLIDA, the off-diagonal cells tell you how much attrition the spine is hiding — that is the real-world reason to write the join this way.


The big one: the PLIDA three-table spine join
The canonical PLIDA analytical question joins three tables: demographics on the universal spine_id, an agency spine table to bridge identifiers, and a large claims fact table keyed on the agency identifier. For MBS at 372 million claim rows this is benchmarked as T3 on the benchmarks page. Arrow lost: the Acero engine was killed by the OS during our benchmark run. DuckDB handles it via native storage and buffer-pool paging. The dplyr code is identical to what arrow would accept; we simply do not run it.


Code
mbs_tbl &lt;- tbl(con, "mbs") |&gt; rename_with(tolower)



DuckDBArrow (not run)




